                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Portland July 25<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1887.<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear sir&#33;&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>I took the liberty to telegraph<lb/> to you for any information you<lb/> might have concerning one Rosedola<lb/> or Rosendale&#44; an apostate&#44; who<lb/> under the name of Dr Wad&#45;El&#45;Ward<lb/> is lecturing in churches and halls<lb/> here under the auspices of the<lb/> Y. M. C. A.<lb/></p>
            <p>I have had occasion&#44; several times<lb/> to contradict&#44; to friends&#44; some of his<lb/> assertions concerning the history<lb/> feelings and religion of our people&#44;<lb/> but of course have entered into no<lb/> public controversy&#44; nor do I propose<lb/> so to do.  He has announced an<lb/> intention however to address the<lb/> Masonic lodges of the city<lb/> August second&#44; next&#44; and then &#38;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>there is just where I desire<lb/> to meet him&#44; where he cannot<lb/> get away from me&#44; nor appeal<lb/> to a new audience with an<lb/> exparte statement.  I desire<lb/> to be posted as far as possible<lb/> in the man&#39;s doings&#44; some of which<lb/> I have learned&#59; and being under<lb/> the impression that he &#34;worked&#34;<lb/> Philadelphia some years ago<lb/> I applied to you.  He is reaping<lb/> a rich harvest here and<lb/> proposes to travel through<lb/> all the surrounding country&#44; with<lb/> his &#34;lovely wife Rebecca&#34;<lb/></p>
            <p>With high regards<lb/>
                very truly yours<lb/>
                D. S. Cohen<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev Sabato Morais&#44; Philada.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
